section.subsection:
                The Pairing interface provides some methods to access the groups:

                /* Return G1 */
Field G1 = pairing.getG1();

/* Return G2 */
Field G2 = pairing.getG2();

/* Return GT */
Field GT = pairing.getGT();

/* Return Zr */
Field Zr = pairing.getZr();

li.source:
import it.unisa.dia.gas.plaf.jpbc.pairing.PairingFactory;

CurveParams curveParams = new CurveParams().load("curve.properties");
Pairing pairing = PairingFactory.getPairing(curveParams);

import it.unisa.dia.gas.plaf.jpbc.pbc.PBCPairing;

CurveParams curveParams = new CurveParams().load("curve.properties");
Pairing pairing = new PBCPairing(curveParams);

import it.unisa.dia.gas.plaf.jpbc.pairing.PairingFactory;

CurveParams curveParams = new CurveParams().load("curve.properties");
// Ask to the PairingFactory to try to use the PBC wrapper when possible.
PairingFactory.getInstance().setUsePBCWhenPossible(true);
Pairing pairing = PairingFactory.getPairing(curveParams);

section.subsection:


                    The following applies the bilinear map described by pairing. The element
                    out
                    will be set to the map
                    applied to
                    in1
                    and
                    in2
                    , that is
                    out = e(in1, in2)
                    .
                    in1
                    must be in the group
                    G1
                    ,
                    in2
                    must be in the
                    group
                    G2
                    . out will lie in the group
                    GT
                    .


Element in1 = pairing.getG1().newRandomElement();
Element in2 = pairing.getG2().newRandomElement();
Element out = pairing.pairing(in1, in2);




                    There is another way to apply the pairing which uses a pre-processing technic . So if you have for many times
                    the same first input (that in G1) you can use the following to reduce the time used to compute
                    the pairing.


                    The reference interface is
                    it.unisa.dia.gas.jpbc.PairingPreProcessing



/* Get ready to perform a pairing whose first input is in1,
   store the results of time-saving precomputation in ppp. */

Element in1 = pairing.getG1().newRandomElement();
PairingPreProcessing ppp = pairing.pairing(in1);

/* Compute the pairing using in2 and the preprocessed information
   stored in ppp. The inputs to the pairing are the element
   previously used to initialize ppp and the element in2. */

Element in2 = pairing.getG2().newRandomElement();
Element out = ppp.pairing(in2);


                Furthermore, you can compute the product of pairings in one shot using
                the following;


Element in1[] = new Element[5];
for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++)
    in1[i] = pairing.getG1().newRandomElement();

Element in2[] = new Element[5];
for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++)
    in2[i] = pairing.getG2().newRandomElement();

Element out = pairing.pairing(in1, in2);
